## Introduction

First of all I want to point out that this issue may be more important than you may think at first because it may happen in every monogame, even if it's pure 2D. Even worse, a usual player that owns 3D Vision may not even have the idea that the graphic glitches he is seeing may be related to 3D Vision, he forgot to deactivate.
## Symptoms

So now for the issue itself. After experiencing random graphic glitches I wrote a sample code as simple as possible (see below). In order to run it you will need
1. a new plain Windows Desktop monogame project
2. a resource file named "pixel.xnb" which is a 2D-Texture that simply contains a single black pixel.

What it does is to draw a horizontal black line with a height of 5 pixels on a white background and move it vertical in steps of 5 pixels every frame. Works perfectly with 3D Vision deactivated but if 3D Vision kicks in the following happens:

![timingglitch](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/13534999/8926879/966c40c4-3513-11e5-91e5-6c76f57c98c8.jpg)

It turned out that it was impossible to get a regular screenshot from the glitch, so I needed to take a photograph of my screen. So please ignore the unsharp grey stripes - they are a side-effect of taking a photograph of the screen and not really there. What is the real glitch are the 3 thin horizontal lines, there only should be one, which is the lowest of them.

If you could see the movement: The glitch lines appear to be flickering (I think about 20 times/second, see my theory below). But taking a video of the glitch is even more impossible (120 Hz video camera, anyone? :D ). Then the glitch lines change their position at random points of time.

Looking through my 3D glasses it appeared that the glitch lines are only in the half-picture intended for the right eye, the left eye looks normal.
## Theory

 After some research about the internal workings of DirectX graphics and how Monogame uses it I came up with the following theory how this happens:
1. Monogame creates a swapchain in the video memory which consists of a screen buffer and 2 back buffers
2. since 3D Vision needs 2 half-pictures it creates secondary buffers for the right eye. It doesnt tell the application anything about that (wouldn't be possible with older 3D games that are automatically converted into stereo 3D)
3. When a Frame should be drawn, Monogame sends draw instructions to the graphics card and waits until they are executed, then presents the next buffer in the swapchain.
4. Monogame (or SharpDX?) uses some unusual way to determine when the draw operations are finished. At least I assume it must be unusual since I never noticed the same problem in other 3D games. The call returns when the first buffer has been drawn, the secondary buffer has not yet been drawn.
5. Under normal circumstances the next Frame is drawn now. If that happens the preceding draw operations are cancelled. The secondary buffer remains unchanged.
6. only at random times (for example when the operating system gives cpu time to another thread or process) the graphics card is given enough time to execute the drawing operations for the seondary buffer. Then the secondary buffer is changed.
7. The screen is presented with the contents of the primary and secondary buffers. Since the secondary buffer contains an old version of the drawing from some random point of time in the past, a flickering ghost will appear. Since there are 3 secondary buffers it flickers at a rate of

   120 Hz / 2 (half pictures/second) / 3 (buffers/half-picture) = 20 Hz

   There are up to 3 ghosts, because we have 3 secondary buffers.
## Workaround

To test my theory I just gave the graphics card more time to finish by adding a Thread.Sleep() to the draw cycle. To test remove the slashes from the line `Thread.Sleep( (int)gameTime.ElapsedGameTime.TotalMilliseconds/8);` in my code sample. I found the appropriate amount of time with trial and error, it may be system dependent.

On my system this removes all the graphic glitches.
## Suggestions for Solution

The second best solution would be to deactivate 3D Vision in Monogame completely. There is an API (nvapi.dll) that allows game developers to control 3D vision, so Monogame would need to check wether it is present and make the appropriate calls.

The best solution would be of course to fix the source of the problem since this would allow to write 3D-vision compatible games with Monogame.
## Code

``` csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using Microsoft.Xna.Framework;
using Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Graphics;
using Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Input;

namespace Game1
{
    public class Game1 : Game
    {
        GraphicsDeviceManager graphics;
        SpriteBatch spriteBatch;
        private Texture2D pixel;

        private int linepos = 0;

        private Rectangle screen;

        public Game1()
        {
            graphics = new GraphicsDeviceManager(this);
            graphics.IsFullScreen = true;
            graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = 1920;
            graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = 1080;
            Content.RootDirectory = "Content";
        }
        protected override void Initialize()
        {
            graphics.IsFullScreen = true;

            this.IsFixedTimeStep = true;
            this.TargetElapsedTime = new System.TimeSpan(166666L);
            screen = GraphicsDevice.Adapter.CurrentDisplayMode.TitleSafeArea;

            base.Initialize();
        }
        protected override void LoadContent()
        {
            spriteBatch = new SpriteBatch(GraphicsDevice);
            pixel = Content.Load<Texture2D>("pixel");
        }
        protected override void UnloadContent()
        {
        }

        protected override void Update(GameTime gameTime)
        {
            if (GamePad.GetState(PlayerIndex.One).Buttons.Back == ButtonState.Pressed || Keyboard.GetState().IsKeyDown(Keys.Escape))
                Exit();

            linepos = (linepos + 5) % screen.Height;

            base.Update(gameTime);
        }

        protected override void Draw(GameTime gameTime)
        {
            GraphicsDevice.Clear(Color.White);
            spriteBatch.Begin(samplerState: SamplerState.LinearWrap);
            spriteBatch.Draw(pixel, new Rectangle(0, linepos, screen.Width, 5), new Rectangle(0, 0, screen.Width, 5), Color.White);
            spriteBatch.End();
            //Thread.Sleep( (int)gameTime.ElapsedGameTime.TotalMilliseconds/8);

            base.Draw(gameTime);
        }
    }
}
```

